caption: b'Customers love what small businesses bring to their communities. Their loyalty to those businesses helps turn them into places that locals eagerly return to over and over again. We asked customers from shops like Cliff\xe2\x80\x99s Variety in San Francisco, Ching Ching Cha tea room  in Washington D.C., and J.Landress Brass shop in New York what makes the businesses they love special. \n\nWhat makes your favorite small business great?'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cAnyone can make magic and magic is for anyone.\xe2\x80\x9d

When former cancer nurse, Holly, and her friend, Bree, made their first princess yarn wig, it was for a friend\xe2\x80\x99s little girl recovering from chemotherapy who wanted something soft to cover her head. Over five years later, Holly and Bree have sent over 30,000 Magic Yarn Wigs to children battling cancer in 51 countries. 

They are true champions that inspire giving back. 

\xe2\x80\x9cFor every wig that we send out to a child, between three to four different \xe2\x80\x98Magic Makers\xe2\x80\x99 have been involved in making that wig, from knitting to buying the supplies. Our volunteers are from all walks of life: Boy Scouts, grandmothers, prison inmates, school clubs, national honor societies, men and women in the armed services, and NFL players. All helping us spread magic to children with cancer.\xe2\x80\x9d

Holly and Bree use the @facebookapp to share stories of brave children receiving wigs, and use Facebook Live to stay connected with their community of volunteers and Magic Makers who are constantly helping give back. 

Holly and Bree are two of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cMy daughter, Luna, and I were following the wildfires in California. I saw a news story about a man who was able to start up a motorhome parked on the side of his house and escape the fire. He said that he was just so grateful to have a home. It just struck me like a bolt of lightning that there are RVs everywhere. I turned to Luna and I said, \xe2\x80\x98What do you think about finding an RV and driving it to California and giving it to a family who lost their home for Thanksgiving?\xe2\x80\x99 And she had this big smile on her face.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Woody started @emergencyrv initially to help one displaced family with one donated RV. Since then, it has become a thriving online community where Woody connects with families in need, as well as individuals wanting to donate RVs. For Woody, the response has been overwhelming. 
 
\xe2\x80\x9cI put the word out on my @facebookapp profile. All my friends and family shared it. As we continued on our journey, people started reaching out and offering to help. We connected with one firefighter in Oregon who had lost her home in the wildfires. Luna and I immediately knew we needed to get her an RV and help somebody who was already giving so much.\xe2\x80\x9d 
 
Woody and Luna stay in touch with the families they help and consider them members of their own extended family. Their generosity has become an inspiration to everyone whose lives they touch.
 
Woody and Luna of two of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cFor me, flying rescue missions for these animals is incredibly important. Statistics show that about 1800 dogs get killed every single day in the US. When I see photos of them in shelters in terrible situations\xe2\x80\x94crammed into a tiny space with dozens of dogs that are abused on a regular basis\xe2\x80\x94 I try to be one of the many voices for the voiceless.\xe2\x80\x9d 

Eduard, a volunteer pilot with @pilotsnpaws, has personally flown over 60 dogs to safety from kill shelters to rescue organizations and foster families. Given the rising threat shelter animals face to being euthanized, especially during COVID, Eduard can\xe2\x80\x99t imagine a more important way of giving back. 

\xe2\x80\x9cOne of my main goals is to inspire other pilots to volunteer. If I can get one more, two more, three more pilots to join our rescue missions and help save lives, that would make me very happy.\xe2\x80\x9d

Eduard stays in touch with other pilots via @WhatsApp and is always at-the-ready to rescue an animal in need. He is currently mentoring young pilots to help them get their license so more diehard animal advocates are cleared for take-off. 

Eduard is one of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cWhen I started this initiative, the purpose was really just to go out and do something kind. I had no idea that it would grow into a passion and something that was needed, not just in the city of Philadelphia, but all over the world.\xe2\x80\x9d

When professional barber Brennon started giving haircuts to people experiencing homelessness, he wanted to give some positivity and change to a forgotten group. It inspired a new movement of giving across the country. Other barbers and cosmetologists started reaching out to help, and he formed the Cutz of Compassion crew. Their first tour went up and down the east coast, giving 3,000 people haircuts in three years.

\xe2\x80\x9cMy wife was recording a video on @FacebookApp Live and somebody recognized the man whose hair I was cutting. He is somebody\xe2\x80\x99s family. They had lost touch with him and didn\xe2\x80\x99t know he was homeless. They got in touch and reconnected. It was really cool to see that happen.\xe2\x80\x9d

Several tours and 5,000 haircuts later, Brennon is still on the street from sunup to sundown giving cuts and making a difference in people\xe2\x80\x99s lives.

Brennon is one of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'As the Season of Giving kicks off, there are so many inspiring ways people are giving back to others. Have you thought about how you could give back this Giving Season? All it takes is personal passion and small actions that inspire like-minded people to help create a community and spread the word.

Like friends Holly and Bree, who are spreading magic and joy to children battling cancer by making princess yarn wigs. Or Woody and his daughter, Luna, who are helping donate RVs to families who have lost their homes to wildfires. Or Eduard, who is combining his love of flying and animals to run rescue missions for dogs and cats in kill shelters to rescue organizations and foster families.
 
Whether you\xe2\x80\x99re starting a Facebook Fundraiser, or getting the word out for your favorite charity or non-profit on your personal page, it doesn\xe2\x80\x99t take much to make a difference this season. 
 
Join us in celebrating the countless ways people are giving back. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cThe Magic Yarn Project isn\xe2\x80\x99t just about giving wigs to kids with cancer but giving others an opportunity to serve families in need.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Former cancer nurse, Holly, and her friend, Bree, spend every day of the year giving a little bit of joy and magic to children battling cancer. Since 2015, they have been the heart and soul behind @themagicyarnproject, which makes soft princess and superhero yarn wigs for kids to wear after chemotherapy treatment. More than just a wig, it\xe2\x80\x99s a community of volunteers who have come together online to make a difference in a child\xe2\x80\x99s life when he or she need it most.
 
\xe2\x80\x9cThere is nothing better than seeing a little girl with cancer put on a wig and dance around in her yard.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Holly and Bree have found the power of the @facebookapp to build their community of \xe2\x80\x98Magic Makers\xe2\x80\x99, sharing stories of brave children on the platform and using Facebook Live to stay connected with their community of volunteers and Magic Makers who have helped send over 30,000 wigs to children in 51 countries. 
 
Holly and Bree are two of the of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cMy concept of volunteering has changed over the years since I started flying rescue missions for cats and dogs. Now I fly with a purpose.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Pilot and restaurateur Eduard used to fly planes for pleasure. Now, he flies with renewed purpose as a volunteer pilot with @pilotsnpaws, a non-profit that flies transport rescue missions for dogs and cats in high-kill shelters to no-kill rescue organizations and foster families. For Eduard, flying animals to safety and giving them a second chance makes this the perfect volunteering mission. 
 
\xe2\x80\x9cFor me helping to find homes for these animals is incredibly important. These animals are in need of foster homes, medical care and a second chance.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
So far, Eduard has flown over 60 dogs to safety and new homes, finding his own creative way to give back. He shares his rescue stories with his community on the @facebookapp and uses @whatsapp to stay in contact with fellow pilots always at-the-ready to fly a rescue mission for an animal in need. 
 
Eduard is one of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cIf we can deliver an RV to somebody who is suddenly homeless, that\xe2\x80\x99s the first step to helping their recovery.\xe2\x80\x9d 
 
@wfaircloth11 and his daughter, Luna, know a thing or two about giving back. After seeing families lose their homes in the destructive California wildfires, Woody started @emergencyrv, which donates refurbished RVs to families who have lost their homes in these natural disasters. They have delivered nearly 90 RVs to displaced families in need of a roof over their head. 
 
\xe2\x80\x9cI can\xe2\x80\x99t describe how powerful a moment that is to be able to provide shelter\xe2\x80\x94such a basic human need. Home is the safest place we have.\xe2\x80\x9d

Woody and Luna\xe2\x80\x99s efforts caught the attention of friends and new supporters on social media. Now, Woody uses his Facebook group to share out his incredible stories with his community of countless volunteers who stepped up to help him give back. 
 
Woody and Luna are two of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cIt costs absolutely nothing to give back, to do something nice for somebody who can give you nothing in return.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Professional barber Brennon started @haircut4homeless to help a population of people who needed his positivity and encouragement. He went from cutting his regular customers\xe2\x80\x99 hair to seeking out people experiencing homelessness who were looking for compassion, somebody to talk to, and a free haircut.
 
\xe2\x80\x9cWhen they sit in my chair, the haircut is kind of like a new beginning.\xe2\x80\x9d
 
Brennon\xe2\x80\x99s razor and scissors may bring a physical change, but his words of wisdom have lifted many at a time when they need it most. He spreads his love of giving back using @instagram to share out his stories and promote his $2 Tuesdays that help cover his costs to make a difference with a razor and a smile.
 
Brennon is one of countless individuals giving back every day, but especially during Giving Season. See link in bio to learn more about ways to give back this Season of Giving.'

b"Small businesses do more than sell products and services to people. They create community. \xe2\x80\x9cWe\xe2\x80\x99re proud to employ local people and contribute to our tax base,\xe2\x80\x9d says Rebecca M., who runs @peggyjeanspies with her mother Jeanne P., in Columbia, MO. 

\xe2\x80\x9cSmall businesses always support fundraisers, local sports leagues for kids, and school districts. That's the intangible part of it. The tangible part \xe2\x80\x94 well, that\xe2\x80\x99s our homemade pie with recipes from scratch.\xe2\x80\x9d Rebecca also writes a widely-read blog and coaches area students on business. 

What do small businesses in your area do to help your community?"

b'Thanksgiving reminds us to be grateful for the deep bonds small businesses forge with members of their community. Jothi P. recalls a moment when his favorite bakery, @peggyjeanspies in Columbia, MO, a mother-daughter business led by Jeanne P. and her daughter Rebecca M., went above and beyond for him. Read on to see how they comforted Jothi P.\n\nHow do your local businesses step up in times of need?'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cPie baking is a lost art in our rapid culture of convenience, but we bake completely from scratch, using my grandmother and great-grandmother's recipes,\xe2\x80\x9d says Rebecca M. of @peggyjeanspies, the Columbia, MO bakery she runs alongside her mother, Jeanne P.

Step inside and you get a view of the entire kitchen filled with their staff of locals, keeping homespun tradition alive and well. 

Where\xe2\x80\x99s your favorite place to get pie for Thanksgiving?"

b"@theresilientband is a Pennsylvania-based band made up of three Veterans and one professional musician. The band met at Walter Reed Hospital where Tim, Nate, and Dom were receiving rehabilitation for combat wounds and Greg was part of an outreach program. Music became both a form of catharsis to deal with PTSD, and a path to reconnect with the world.

\xe2\x80\x9cThere are so many rock bands, there're so many rap groups, so many solo artists, but this is different. When we play, people have never seen anything like us before\xe2\x80\xa6 It\xe2\x80\x99s music, but it\xe2\x80\x99s also a demonstration of the human spirit.\xe2\x80\x9d - Greg, Band Member and Volunteer at Walter Reed Hospital

\xe2\x80\x9cWe have diverse backgrounds, beliefs, and come from different places, but we have a shared mission \xe2\x80\x94 to heal through music and reconnect with the world.\xe2\x80\x9d - Nate, Guitarist

The Resilient are a rock band, a support group, activists, friends, and Veterans. Service is one of many parts of their story. Let\xe2\x80\x99s celebrate the talent within the Veteran community."

b'\xe2\x80\x9cCertainly, without the military, I wouldn\xe2\x80\x99t be where I am today. From the positives to the negatives, who I am today is a direct reflection of that experience in the military.\xe2\x80\x9d - Duane, Army Veteran

Duane\xe2\x80\x99s love of fashion design became an unlikely therapy to deal with PTSD, helping him find peace, reinvent himself, and ultimately rediscover who he really was with his fashion line Topping Designs.

\xe2\x80\x9cIt became more than just about me. We were sending the message forward that others could be more than a label. I shared the clothes on Facebook and Instagram. Just put it out there. No idea how people would respond. And things started to take a life of their own.\xe2\x80\x9d

Duane is a fashion designer, a husband, an activist, an artist, a friend, a mentor, and a Veteran. Service is one of many parts of his story. This Veterans Day, let\xe2\x80\x99s celebrate the talent within the Veteran community.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cMy father was in the military and he was a pioneer in his own right. I feel so honored to be following his footsteps.\xe2\x80\x9d

Olga, a Lieutenant Colonel who served with the US Air Force, was the first Latina fighter pilot, military instructor, and commercial pilot. Despite her achievements, Olga\xe2\x80\x99s intention was never to be a first. Her priority has always been her family. 

\xe2\x80\x9cMy husband, my children, my grandchildren are the most important things to me. Work hard for your family and everything else will fall into line.\xe2\x80\x9d

Passionate about her Puerto Rican heritage, Olga and her family often return to reconnect with their Latin roots - experiencing the culture, food, and traditional customs. 

Olga is a friend, a pilot, a Puerto Rican, a woman, a daughter, a wife, a mother, and a Veteran. Service is one of many parts of her story. This Veterans Day, let\xe2\x80\x99s celebrate the talent within the Veteran community.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI am a musician. I am a bull rider. I am a technologist. I\xe2\x80\x99m engaged. I\xe2\x80\x99m a stepparent. I\xe2\x80\x99m your neighbor. And there are many other people like me.\xe2\x80\x9d

For Lee (they/them), coming out means defining the person they always wanted to be, and showing up as their authentic self no matter what environment they\xe2\x80\x99re in.

\xe2\x80\x9cI am very proud to be trans. To be non-binary. Because I think people think we only exist in these particular spaces and that is not the case.\xe2\x80\x9d

:clapper_board:: @rivergallo

b'For Kite (they/them), coming out is a story of letting go of everything that was holding them back. Instead of being scared of the future, they learned to embrace the present with support from their family and online community. 

\xe2\x80\x9cI think for me, coming out is letting it all go. Whether it\xe2\x80\x99s a small thing, like changing your pronouns on Facebook, or letting people know you\xe2\x80\x99re dating someone of the same gender, it\xe2\x80\x99s the little everyday things.

\xe2\x80\x9cThe reality is that you come out all the time. You come out daily.\xe2\x80\x9d

:camera:: @devyngalindo 
:clapper_board:: @rivergallo

#ComingOut2020
#SharewithPride'

b'Lieutenant Colonel Marisol Chalas\xe2\x80\x99s story of resilience is about breaking barriers, for herself and other women in the Army, by rising above obstacles. Here are some objects that gave her strength on her way to becoming who she is today.'

b"\xe2\x80\x9cI always tell people I'm so proud to be Hispanic American, because I can embrace the American, but I also have the Latina in me that will never leave my blood. I think seeing my parents working hard, being humble, has shaped me to be the person that I am.\xe2\x80\x9d 

Lieutenant Colonel Marisol Chalas immigrated from the Dominican Republic when she was just nine years old. Her story of resilience is about breaking barriers for herself and other women in the Army, by rising above obstacles. She became the first Latina Black Hawk pilot in the Army National Guard. She later transitioned to the U.S. Army Reserves and currently serves as the Legislative Assistant to the 37th Vice Chief of Staff of the Army. 

\xe2\x80\x9cMy first aviation unit was not very female friendly, but I overcame that and became a much stronger person. Resilience means setting goals, falling down, dusting yourself off, and saying \xe2\x80\x98I got this.\xe2\x80\x99 It means if you have to take a step back and be like: \xe2\x80\x98God, why me?,\xe2\x80\x99 you lean on your friends and you remind yourself what your goal is. And no matter what you just keep trucking forward. Querer es poder. To want is to achieve.\xe2\x80\x9d 

The appearance of U.S. Department of Defense (DoD) visual information does not imply or constitute DoD endorsement."

b'For D\xe2\x80\x99Santi (he/him), born and raised in Santa Fe, New Mexico, coming out has been a journey full of music, heritage, and love. 

\xe2\x80\x9cComing out to me is saying, I am D\xe2\x80\x99Santi. I am here. I walk this earth like anybody else. And I want the same things.

\xe2\x80\x9cI was 48 years old when the decision was made to transition. To look at old pictures it seems like a whole lifetime ago. Sometimes I don\xe2\x80\x99t recognize myself and sometimes I\xe2\x80\x99m OK with that, you know?\xe2\x80\x9d 

:camera:: @devyngalindo 
:clapper_board:: @rivergallo

#ComingOut2020
#ShareWithPride'

\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI had a hard time coming out to the snowboarding community\xe2\x80\xa6 I didn\xe2\x80\x99t know where I would fit in.\xe2\xa0\x80

b'\xe2\x80\x9cWe were made for community. We were made for connecting. That's what keeps us alive. So checking in is a lifeline to somebody and you never know what day they'll need it.\xe2\x80\x9d - Sha, Social Worker and good friend, living in Columbus, OH.

In honor of the World Health Organization's World Mental Health Day, we\xe2\x80\x99re sharing the story of B. and Sha. \xe2\x80\x9cHow is Your Heart?\xe2\x80\x9dis the question Sha asked her college friend B, which unlocked a tidal wave of emotions that B had been holding on to for years. Though they haven\xe2\x80\x99t seen each other in a decade, their bond is one of love, respect, and not taking \xe2\x80\x98I\xe2\x80\x99m fine,\xe2\x80\x99 for an answer. That phone call check-in was the catalyst to Sha helping B through. 

If you are looking for resources, Facebook has partnered with experts to provide tips on your emotional health. To access these tips, search for "Emotional Health" in the Facebook app.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cI know two negatives don\xe2\x80\x99t make a positive sometimes, but maybe if we talk through it together, we will help each other out. It\xe2\x80\x99s easier to climb a mountain as a team rather than by yourself. I need my teammate.\xe2\x80\x9d - Ruben, a hairdresser and close friend to Mary in California. 

In honor of the World Health Organization's World Mental Health Day, we\xe2\x80\x99re sharing the story of Ruben and Mary, who became friends in a salon, and have been inseparable since. Well, until the pandemic. Not being able to see each other during quarantine was really weighing on Ruben\xe2\x80\x99s mind -- especially since he knew his client Mary was dealing with a series of hardships. And Mary wasn\xe2\x80\x99t responding to his attempts to reach out to her via phone and Facebook messages. This story shows how persistence, love and care (plus a bit of color) can change everything. 

If you are looking for resources, Facebook has partnered with experts to provide tips on your emotional health. To access these tips, search for "Emotional Health" in the Facebook app.'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cIf there are any people in your life that you love and that you also haven\xe2\x80\x99t talked to in awhile, because you just think that, \xe2\x80\x98Oh, they\xe2\x80\x99re fine. They\xe2\x80\x99re doing great.\xe2\x80\x99 Those are probably the people that you need to reach out to.\xe2\x80\x9d - Lexy, a filmmaker living at home in Troy, Missouri. \xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cWhat Do You Love?\xe2\x80\x9d These are the four words that Lexy asked Levi, which led to her discovering that her friend of 15 years had a love for reading. That question during their video call led to a two-person book club to stay connected,  and it proved the catalyst for helping Levi through his difficult time. Sometimes, a small gesture can go a long way. \xe2\xa0\x80

b"\xe2\x80\x9cOne thing that I've seen from the Mayan community is that they're not giving up on their culture. They\xe2\x80\x99re keeping it alive with traditional music, language, textiles. My mom and my wife weave all of my clothing \xe2\x80\x94 it\xe2\x80\x99s a big part of our culture. It\xe2\x80\x99s the work of art that gets passed on between generations.\xe2\x80\x9d 

Henry Sales (Mintz Xalx Nantz in Mam) moved to Oakland from Guatemala nine years ago. His story of resilience is about preserving his culture and traditions far away from his hometown of San Juan Atitan (Xjan Xwan in Mam) as he teaches the language and history of his people.

\xe2\x80\x9cI\xe2\x80\x99m proud that I didn\xe2\x80\x99t give up on my language. When I first started teaching Mam, only two people showed up for the first session. But now, two years later, I have 150 students registered and taking the class at Laney College. Living in California and not giving up on my culture \xe2\x80\x94 that\xe2\x80\x99s an example of resilience.\xe2\x80\x9d"

b'Felix Navarro & Felipe Abrahao\xe2\x80\x99s story of resilience is about following their dreams of becoming @thejuicyleaf owners, no matter the obstacles and sacrifices required. Here are some objects that gave them strength on their way to becoming who they are today.\n\n#latinxheritagemonth #hispanicheritagemonth'

b'\xe2\x80\x9cTo us The Juicy Leaf is a magical place. And I feel like it is for a lot of people. When you walk into the store, you feel the love and passion that we put into it.\xe2\x80\x9d - Felix

Felix Navarro is a Mexican-American business owner of @thejuicyleaf, a succulent boutique that he manages with his work and life partner, Felipe Abrahao. His story of resilience is about following his dreams no matter the obstacles and sacrifices required. 

\xe2\x80\x9cSince I was a little kid, I always had my hands in the dirt. I learned everything I know from my mom. To leave my secure job for my passion was absolutely terrifying. I would second-guess myself a lot. I went from being an executive in corporate America, making really good money, to selling succulents at flea markets.

Resilience to me means to never give up, to evolve, to pivot. No matter what comes at you, you just keep fighting and doing what you need to do.\xe2\x80\x9d - Felix

#latinxheritagemonth #hispanicheritagemonth'

b'Eriberto (EribertoOriol.com) and his son Estevan\xe2\x80\x99s bond is behind their most groundbreaking work in photography. b'Black LGBTQ+ people have always played a critical role in the fight for equality, with activists like Marsha P. Johnson at the forefront of the Stonewall riots. Today, we\xe2\x80\x99re honoring the legacy of LGBTQ+ activists by showcasing and celebrating inspiring leaders.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Meet Hope Giselle @hopedisguised (she/her), a trans activist and founder of the AllowMe Movement, which works to help of young LGBTQ+ people of color find and succeed in leadership positions. \xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI got the idea for The #AllowMe Movement in my freshman year of college. I wanted to put it in spaces and cities where LGBTQ youth of color could benefit from it. So many people when I\xe2\x80\x99m pitching will say \xe2\x80\x98well, there\xe2\x80\x99s already programs like that.\xe2\x80\x99 Not for Black and Brown people.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cWe try to connect with students to show them people outside of stereotypical careers. Just because you\xe2\x80\x99re Queer and Black does not mean you have to be a stylist or a make-up artist or that you have to go into the arts. You can be Black and Queer and a doctor, but a lot of students aren\xe2\x80\x99t hearing those messages.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cMy ultimate goal is for folks to be able to dictate what their freedom looks like. No longer making decisions based on choosing between safety and happiness. My work helps to embolden the voiceless, educate those who lack the resources and gives access to the folks who aren\xe2\x80\x99t invited to the table.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
:camera_with_flash:: @quillemons'

b'Black LGBTQ+ people have always played a critical role in the fight for equality, with activists like Marsha P. Johnson at the forefront of the Stonewall riots. Today, we\xe2\x80\x99re honoring the legacy of LGBTQ+ activists by showcasing and celebrating inspiring leaders.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
Meet Jevon Martin @stonecoldlegend (he/him), a trans activist and the founder and executive director of Princess Janae Place in New York City, an organization that supports the trans homeless population.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI started in the LBGTQ+ community in my teenage years. In the Village, we have different groups, houses in the ballroom scene. Being on the Pier, you\xe2\x80\x99d see the different houses voguing against each other, dancing and playing double-dutch and stuff. As the night came, the wee hours of the morning came, people would still be out there. And I realized these people don\xe2\x80\x99t have homes. They stay outside. Like literally outside. \xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cEventually I started a non-profit [that supports homeless trans people]. My ultimate goal is to have housing for all. It is a human right to have shelter. \xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cI use my voice to be visible and stand up for injustices against discrimination of LGBTQ+ people and killing of trans people. My advice to activists that want to make their voices heard is to keep the focus on the people. Do not take it to heart, the negative and disrespect that comes with this work. There are people that don\xe2\x80\x99t like us, and will never understand who we are.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
:camera_with_flash:: @quillemons'

b'Black LGBTQ+ people have always played a critical role in the fight for equality, with activists like Marsha P. Johnson at the forefront of the Stonewall riots. Today, on the 51st anniversary of Stonewall, we\xe2\x80\x99re honoring the legacy of LGBTQ+ activists by showcasing and celebrating inspiring leaders.\xe2\xa0\x80

Today we\xe2\x80\x99re featuring Jordan Medley @jordan.medley (he/him), a dancer who works for the Arts Council of Winston-Salem and Forsyth County where he advocates for equitable access to grant funding and arts programming.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cIn a way, I see my Blackness as the place where I found confidence and power to accept being gay. Being Black I\xe2\x80\x99ve had to grow a tough skin, learn to love myself, and to work a thousand times harder than most. I\xe2\x80\x99ve literally told myself, \xe2\x80\x98If I can be Black and proud, I definitely can love being my gay self.\xe2\x80\x99\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cThere\xe2\x80\x99s not a lot of representation for artists like me. I feel like that\xe2\x80\x99s disheartening but I also know where I am. I get the territory. You know, we\xe2\x80\x99re in the South. I get that.\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\x80\x9cBut what I take pride in everyday is that being in my role [at the arts council], I gain more visibility. I think what that says to our community and our state is Black gay men have something to say. And we are assets to this community.\xe2\x80\x9d\xe2\xa0\x80
\xe2\xa0\x80
:camera_with_flash:: @quillemons'

b'We recognize June 19, 1865 as the final day of slavery in the United States. Known as Juneteenth, it commemorates the moment the last remaining enslaved people in Texas learned of their freedom, established by the Emancipation Proclamation two years before. 
To honor this day, we\xe2\x80\x99re taking time to become better listeners and greater-informed individuals, so we\xe2\x80\x99re more equipped to take action. This won\xe2\x80\x99t be a conversation reserved for one day, it\xe2\x80\x99s one we\xe2\x80\x99ll continue having until racial injustice is no longer a reality. 
Join us, as we work to elevate and amplify underrepresented voices in society. Visit our Lift Black Voices hub on @facebookapp and the @instagram Act for Racial Justice Guide to find ways to learn more and participate.
